WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.360
Hello everyone, my name is Andreas Hofheinz and today I'm going to talk about interactive

00:00:10.360 --> 00:00:13.400
multi-layer maps in Shiny with the leafdown package.

00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:18.559
For my talk, I'm going to use the Meteostat weathers record keeper dataset, which contains

00:00:18.559 --> 00:00:23.680
monthly measurements from over 2000 weather stations in the United States, which measure

00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:27.600
variables such as the average temperature and precipitation.

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:31.760
And the question I want to discuss in my talk is, how can we most effectively explore

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:36.799
this data using insights into how to solve common problems and overcome the limitations

00:00:36.799 --> 00:00:39.439
of simple maps.

00:00:39.439 --> 00:00:43.439
When we work with spatial data, well, it is usually helpful to visualize the data on a

00:00:43.439 --> 00:00:47.880
map because of the geographical context and the intuitiveness that comes with it.

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:52.400
So in this example, we see the average temperature per state and already at the first glance

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:57.720
it becomes clear that the average temperature in the South is higher than it is in the North.

00:00:57.720 --> 00:01:03.119
However, one phenomenon we often observe when we aggregate data at higher levels, such as

00:01:03.119 --> 00:01:06.360
the state level, is these heartbreaks at the borders.

00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:10.440
Here it looks like everywhere in California the average temperature is quite high and

00:01:10.440 --> 00:01:15.519
as soon as you take a single step into Oregon, the average temperature drops significantly,

00:01:15.519 --> 00:01:18.199
which is probably not the case, right?

00:01:18.199 --> 00:01:22.519
But the question is, how can we explore this in more detail, or in other words, how can

00:01:22.519 --> 00:01:24.800
we zoom in?

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:29.000
And one way to do this is to trail down to see the data at a more detailed level, in

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:31.139
this case at the county level.

00:01:31.139 --> 00:01:35.440
In this visualization, we see that there is indeed no heartbreaks at the state borders,

00:01:35.440 --> 00:01:39.720
but rather a smooth transition and that the overall high average temperature of California

00:01:39.720 --> 00:01:42.800
is primarily caused by the hot South.

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:46.720
So you might wonder why we don't aggregate the data directly then at the county level

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:50.800
and why do we even bother to aggregate it at the state level in the first place?

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:54.760
Well, let's have a look at what happens when we plot the average temperature for all

00:01:54.760 --> 00:01:57.160
the counties at once.

00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:01.639
In my opinion, this looks quite cluttered and the overall temperature trend is not that

00:02:01.639 --> 00:02:06.760
easy to see, especially when we compare it to the state aggregation map from before.

00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:11.119
I'd argue that it is much easier to see on the right-hand side that the average temperature

00:02:11.119 --> 00:02:14.160
in the South is higher than it is in the North.

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:19.279
And this is one reason why it is really important in many spatial data analysis to switch between

00:02:19.279 --> 00:02:25.160
several aggregation layers to be able to analyze both the overall trends as well as more regional

00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:26.160
trends.

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:31.360
Okay, let's return to our map showing the average temperature per county.

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:36.619
Often, we are interested not only in one variable at the given point in time, but in multiple

00:02:36.619 --> 00:02:40.820
variables and their relationship or their development over time.

00:02:40.820 --> 00:02:48.619
So another question is, how can we visualize multiple variables simultaneously using a map?

00:02:48.619 --> 00:02:53.300
And one approach to do this is to embed the map in a SHINee dashboard and connect it to

00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:56.139
other dashboard elements like charts or tables.

00:02:56.139 --> 00:03:01.380
By selecting the regions of interest in the map, we can then display additional variables

00:03:01.380 --> 00:03:05.080
or their development over time in the other dashboard elements.

00:03:05.080 --> 00:03:09.419
In this case, this allows us to analyze the relationship between the average temperature

00:03:09.500 --> 00:03:17.139
and monthly precipitation as well as the development of the average temperature over time.

00:03:17.139 --> 00:03:20.059
But I don't want to just describe these solutions here.

00:03:20.059 --> 00:03:23.860
I also want to tell you that we have already implemented them in the leafdown package.

00:03:23.860 --> 00:03:28.559
With just a few lines of code, the leafdown package enables you to quickly create maps

00:03:28.559 --> 00:03:34.059
that are embedded in a SHINee dashboard and have selectable regions, which connects the

00:03:34.059 --> 00:03:38.699
map to other dashboard elements, allowing you to visualize multiple variables at once

00:03:38.699 --> 00:03:42.460
as well as their development over time.

00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:46.419
They also have the drill-down and drill-up functionality that allows you to switch between

00:03:46.419 --> 00:03:51.740
several aggregation layers, such as from the state layer to the county layer, to analyze

00:03:51.740 --> 00:03:54.940
the data in more detail.

00:03:54.940 --> 00:03:57.660
And these maps are not limited to only two map layers.

00:03:57.660 --> 00:04:02.460
Instead, we can drill all the way down to the very individual weather stations and compare

00:04:02.460 --> 00:04:07.320
their measurements in the graphs as well, allowing the user to specifically select the

00:04:07.320 --> 00:04:15.160
regions to drill down for, avoids unnecessary clutter, and increases the computational efficiency.

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:19.640
So if you're now interested in quickly creating such flexible and powerful maps by yourself,

00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:23.000
I can highly recommend you have a look at our leafdown package.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:27.920
On this slide, I've provided the GitHub link for you as well as the key facts and features.

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:29.959
Thank you very much for your attention and have a great day.

